{"key":"processedPost-11673938","value":{"id":11673938,"first":11673773,"last":11675206,"when":1261152834,"utime":"12/18/09 06:13 PM","cleanedPost":"This is a bad idea that's been hashed around many, many times before and all the results are right at your fingertips in the search engine.<br />First, it would take a HUGE amount of salt to raise the boiling point in the pressure cooker by even a few degrees.<br />Second, as already pointed out above, at 100C/212 the moisture content of the rye grains would begin evaporating out of the rye since the water in the pressure cooker isn't boiling or building pressure yet.&nbsp; By the end of an hour, there would be no moisture left in your jars.<br />Third, even if you made a salt paste for your PC and managed to raise the temperature at a given pressure, the blowout plug which works on temperature, not pressure, would blow out.<br />Fourth, salt is corrosive and not something you want in your pressure vessel.<br />Fifth, if you're going to be using rye, you need a pressure cooker that goes to 15 psi, but many members here have succeeded with 10 psi by adding 1/3 extra time to the cycle.&nbsp; Soak the grains first to hydrate them, which makes it easier to kill off the bacterial endospores in the grain.<br />RR"}}